<DOC><DOCNO> AP890414-0168 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 1653EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-NukeProtest     04-14 0212</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Nuke Protest,0218</SECOND><HEAD>105 New Arrests at Nevada Site</HEAD><DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Anti-nuclear protesters tried to block trafficin and out of the Nevada Test Site on Friday, and 65 people werearrested on misdemeanor nuisance charges when they failed to movefrom the site's main road.   Forty others were arrested on trespass charges during the night.   Friday's arrests bring to 452 the number of citations issuedsince the annual ``Reclaim the Test Site'' protest began April 7and ending Sunday.   Energy Department spokesman Jim Boyer said 400 protesters showedup near the gates to the site Thursday night and 200 of them satdown on the main road and blocked buses and cars carrying workersto and from the secret desert site.   The traffic was rerouted and the protesters were allowed toremain until dawn, when they were told they would be arrested ifthey did not move.   Boyer said no major traffic delays were reported Friday.   Chris Brown of the sponsoring American Peace Test said theprotesters hoped to block workers from the test site.   Nye County officials say they will no longer prosecuteprotesters who are cited for misdemeanor violations at the remotedesert because of the growing number of protests against thenation's nuclear testing program.</TEXT></DOC>